Scraping data from Twitterâ€™s REST API

Pablo Barbera

December 18, 2017

Weâ€™ll now turn to a different type of Twitter data â€“ static data, either recent tweets or user-level information. This type of data can be retrieved with Twitterâ€™s REST API. We will use the netdemR package here â€“ this is a package that we created in the NetDem lab at USC to facilitate the collection and analysis of Twitter data.

Searching recent tweets

It is possible to download recent tweets, but only up those less than 7 days old, and in some cases not all of them.

Building friend and follower networks

Download friends and followers:

followers <- getFollowers("BJPolS", 
    oauth_folder="../credentials")
## ../credentials/twitter-token.Rdata
## 11 API calls left
## 5000 followers. Next cursor: 1513787500845512127
## 10 API calls left
## 8974 followers. Next cursor: 0
## 9 API calls left
friends <- getFriends("BJPolS", 
    oauth_folder="../credentials")
## ../credentials/twitter-token.Rdata
## 13 API calls left
## 395 friends. Next cursor: 0
## 12 API calls left

What are the most common words that friends of the BJPS Twitter account use to describe themselves on Twitter?

# extract profile descriptions
users <- getUsersBatch(ids=friends, oauth_folder="../credentials")
## 1--395 users left
## 2--295 users left
## 3--195 users left
## 4--95 users left
# create table with frequency of word use
library(quanteda)
## quanteda version 0.99.22
## Using 3 of 4 threads for parallel computing
## 
## Attaching package: 'quanteda'
## The following object is masked from 'package:utils':
## 
##     View
tw <- corpus(users$description[users$description!=""])
dfm <- dfm(tw, remove=c(stopwords("english"), stopwords("spanish"),
                                 "t.co", "https", "rt", "rts", "http"),
           remove_punct=TRUE)
# create wordcloud
par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))
textplot_wordcloud(dfm, rot.per=0, scale=c(3, .50), max.words=100)

Other types of data

The REST API offers also a long list of other endpoints that could be of use at some point, depending on your research interests.

  1. You can search users related to specific keywords:
users <- searchUsers(q="political science", count=100, oauth_folder="../credentials")
## ../credentials/twitter-token.Rdata
users$screen_name[1:10]
##  [1] "ICPSR"           "PolSciRR"        "BrendanNyhan"

##  [7] "TomPepinsky"     "APSAtweets"      "rickhasen"      
## [10] "emayfarris"
  1. If you know the ID of the tweets, you can download it directly from the API. This is useful because tweets cannot be redistributed as part of the replication materials of a published paper, but the list of tweet IDs can be shared:
# Downloading tweets when you know the ID

            filename="../data/old-tweets.json",
            oauth_folder="../credentials")

This is also useful if e.g.Â youâ€™re interested in compiling lists of journalists, because media outlets offer these lists in their profiles.

  1. List of users who retweeted a particular tweet â€“ unfortunately, itâ€™s limited to only 100 most recent retweets.
# Download list of users who retweeted a tweet (unfortunately, only up to 100)

dfm <- dfm(tw, remove=c(stopwords("english"), stopwords("spanish"),
                                 "t.co", "https", "rt", "rts", "http"),
           remove_punct = TRUE)
# create wordcloud
par(mar=c(0,0,0,0))
textplot_wordcloud(dfm, rot.per=0, scale=c(5, .50), max.words=100)

  1. And one final function to convert dates in their internal Twitter format to another format we could work with in R:
# format Twitter dates to facilitate analysis
tweets <- parseTweets("../data/realDonaldTrump.json")
## 1194 tweets have been parsed.
tweets$date <- formatTwDate(tweets$created_at, format="date")
hist(tweets$date, breaks="month")
